<paragraph id="713B6710B210FF9DE259FA200C2B5CA6" blockId="8.[264,1323,1503,1849]" box="[264,555,1503,1529]" pageId="8" pageNumber="45">Distribution and ecology</paragraph>
<paragraph id="713B6710B210FF9DE269F9F80B025E66" blockId="8.[264,1323,1503,1849]" pageId="8" pageNumber="45">
The species is so far only known from two localities in the province of Tulear of central­western 
<collectingCountry id="09932780B210FF9DE29AF9D00C5A5F16" box="[459,602,1583,1609]" name="Madagascar" pageId="8" pageNumber="45">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
, less than 
<quantity id="B67CCAF5B210FF9DE1B9F9D00D485F16" box="[744,840,1583,1609]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="45" unit="km" value="100.0">100 km</quantity>
apart. The size of the Kirindy Forest population was estimated based on the number of leaf rolls found. It appeared to be limited to the edges of short stretch of the track (
<figureCitation id="E9BF7B95B210FF9DE1A4F9800D3E5FC6" box="[757,830,1663,1689]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 9" captionStartId="5.[264,370,1661,1682]" captionTargetBox="[330,1256,283,1610]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[790,1260,916,1615]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 9. Madapoderus pacificus n. sp.: 6 habitat (Kirindy); 7 a female on the leaf of the host plant Grewia; 8 leaf rolls on Grewia in situ; 9 a female rolling up a leaf, near a recently completed roll (photos by S. Biondi)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170528/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="45">
Fig. 
<number id="C74C7537B210FF9DE07CF9800D3E5FC6" box="[813,830,1663,1689]" pageId="8" pageNumber="45" value="6.0">6</number>
</figureCitation>
). In this narrow zone the number of rolls was remarkably high: each branch of the host plant could harbour several dozen of these rolls (
<figureCitation id="E9BF7B95B210FF9DE21AF9300FA15FB6" box="[331,417,1743,1769]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 12" captionStartId="6.[264,370,1505,1526]" captionTargetBox="[264,1322,283,1460]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[689,1325,282,893]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 12. Madapoderus pacificus n. sp.: 10 a leaf roll with two emergence holes; 11 foliage of" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170529/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="45">
Fig. 
<number id="C74C7537B210FF9DE2D3F9300FA15FB6" box="[386,417,1743,1769]" pageId="8" pageNumber="45" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
). The biotope in which the new species was found is classified as primary dry deciduous forest. This forest 
<typeStatus id="AE3FD9B2B210FF9DE135F9080C975E4E" box="[612,663,1783,1809]" pageId="8" pageNumber="45">type</typeStatus>
had a broad geographic range on the island in the past but nowadays occurs only in few restricted zones of western and northern 
<collectingCountry id="09932780B210FF9DE73EF8E00AFF5E66" box="[1135,1279,1823,1849]" name="Madagascar" pageId="8" pageNumber="45">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="713B6710B211FF9CE259FEE30F915869" blockId="9.[264,1325,284,1670]" box="[264,401,284,310]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Life history</paragraph>
<paragraph id="713B6710B211FF9CE269FEBB0DD158D9" blockId="9.[264,1325,284,1670]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">
Observations on the habits of the new species were carried out at the 
<typeStatus id="AE3FD9B2B211FF9CE7C1FEBB0AC25801" box="[1168,1218,324,350]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">type</typeStatus>
locality, during the end of 
<date id="053A41D0B211FF9CE289FE930C9358D9" box="[472,659,364,390]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" value="2003-12">
December 
<number id="C74C7537B211FF9CE109FE930C9358D9" box="[600,659,364,390]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" value="2003.0">2003</number>
</date>
and in early 
<date id="053A41D0B211FF9CE07DFE930DCD58D9" box="[812,973,364,390]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" value="2004-01">
January 
<number id="C74C7537B211FF9CE0DFFE930DCD58D9" box="[910,973,364,390]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</date>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="713B6710B211FF9CE269FE6B0C585B11" blockId="9.[264,1325,284,1670]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Virtually nothing is known, regarding the feeding and reproductive behaviour of the about one hundred species of the tribe Hoplapoderini. No biological information is available in the literature for the African and Madagascan species; a little information is reported for some Asian species, mainly Japanese, but frequently it is only limited to identification of host plants.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="713B6710B211FF9CE269FDA30D4F5A49" blockId="9.[264,1325,284,1670]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">
<taxonomicName id="B6841C93B211FF9CE269FDA30C4C5B2A" box="[312,588,604,629]" class="Insecta" family="Attelabidae" genus="Madapoderus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacificus">
<emphasis id="43F0BB02B211FF9CE269FDA30C4C5B2A" box="[312,588,604,629]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Madapoderus pacificus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is in all its stages of development associated with a species of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="B6841C93B211FF9CE2D4FD7B0C525BC1" authority="Linnaeus" authorityName="Linnaeus" box="[389,594,644,670]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Grewia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="43F0BB02B211FF9CE2D4FD7B0FDC5BC2" box="[389,476,644,669]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Grewia</emphasis>
Linnaeus
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="B6841C93B211FF9CE135FD7B0CEB5BC1" box="[612,747,644,670]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Malvaceae</taxonomicName>
): the identification of the species pending. This woody shrub or tree occurs in the primary dry deciduous forest of Kirindy, small specimens rarely also in thick forest, and flowering individuals commonly grow in forest clearings and along the edges of roads and tracks.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="713B6710B211FF9CE269FCDB0D515AD1" blockId="9.[264,1325,284,1670]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">
Adult 
<taxonomicName id="B6841C93B211FF9CE2D3FCDB0C975A62" box="[386,663,804,829]" class="Insecta" family="Attelabidae" genus="Madapoderus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacificus">
<emphasis id="43F0BB02B211FF9CE2D3FCDB0C975A62" box="[386,663,804,829]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Madapoderus pacificus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
feed on the leaves of this plant after their eclosion from leaf rolls, causing round feeding lesions as typical of Apoderinae in the leaf tissues but generally leaving the main veins intact (
<figureCitation id="E9BF7B95B211FF9CE18CFC8B0D335AD1" box="[733,819,884,910]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 12" captionStartId="6.[264,370,1505,1526]" captionTargetBox="[264,1322,283,1460]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[689,1325,282,893]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 12. Madapoderus pacificus n. sp.: 10 a leaf roll with two emergence holes; 11 foliage of" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170529/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number id="C74C7537B211FF9CE045FC8B0D335AD1" box="[788,819,884,910]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
d).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="713B6710B211FF9CE269FC630D675FD9" blockId="9.[264,1325,284,1670]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">
After mating (not seen), females construct typical attelabid brood rolls from the leaves of their host plant (
<figureCitation id="E9BF7B95B211FF9CE2BDFC3B0C6D5A81" box="[492,621,964,990]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 6 – 9" captionStart-1="FIGURES 10 – 12" captionStartId-0="5.[264,370,1661,1682]" captionStartId-1="6.[264,370,1505,1526]" captionTargetBox-0="[330,1256,283,1610]" captionTargetBox-1="[264,1322,283,1460]" captionTargetId-0="figure@5.[790,1260,916,1615]" captionTargetId-1="figure@6.[689,1325,282,893]" captionTargetPageId-0="5" captionTargetPageId-1="6" captionText-0="FIGURES 6 – 9. Madapoderus pacificus n. sp.: 6 habitat (Kirindy); 7 a female on the leaf of the host plant Grewia; 8 leaf rolls on Grewia in situ; 9 a female rolling up a leaf, near a recently completed roll (photos by S. Biondi)." captionText-1="FIGURES 10 – 12. Madapoderus pacificus n. sp.: 10 a leaf roll with two emergence holes; 11 foliage of" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/170528/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/170529/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">
Figs. 
<number id="C74C7537B211FF9CE161FC3B0C6D5A81" box="[560,621,964,990]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" value="10.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="8.0">8–12</number>
</figureCitation>
). At first, the female makes a cut into the leaf lamina, near the base of the leaf and perpendicular to the midrib. The cut can run from either the left or the right side and begin anywhere along the basal leaf margin, but it always reaches the midrib and often proceeds beyond it (
<figureCitation id="E9BF7B95B211FF9CE195FBC30D0C5D09" box="[708,780,1084,1110]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 9" captionStartId="5.[264,370,1661,1682]" captionTargetBox="[330,1256,283,1610]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[790,1260,916,1615]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 9. Madapoderus pacificus n. sp.: 6 habitat (Kirindy); 7 a female on the leaf of the host plant Grewia; 8 leaf rolls on Grewia in situ; 9 a female rolling up a leaf, near a recently completed roll (photos by S. Biondi)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170528/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number id="C74C7537B211FF9CE1AAFBC30D0C5D09" box="[763,780,1084,1110]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
). In the categorisation of attelabid leaf rolling techniques (
<bibRefCitation id="15151AE1B211FF9CE2C7FB9B0C755D21" author="Zuppa" box="[406,629,1124,1150]" pageId="9" pageNumber="47" refString="Zuppa, A., Osella, G. &amp; Biondi, S. (1994) Parental care in Attelabidae. Ethology Ecology &amp; Evolution, Special Issue, 3, 113 - 118." type="journal article" year="1994">
Zuppa et al., 
<number id="C74C7537B211FF9CE168FB9B0C755D21" box="[569,629,1124,1150]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" value="1994.0">1994</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) 
<taxonomicName id="B6841C93B211FF9CE1D7FB9B0D9C5D22" box="[646,924,1124,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Attelabidae" genus="Madapoderus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pacificus">
<emphasis id="43F0BB02B211FF9CE1D7FB9B0D9C5D22" box="[646,924,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Madapoderus pacificus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
thus falls into the same group as 
<taxonomicName id="B6841C93B211FF9CE259FB730C7B5DF9" authority="Linnaeus. The" authorityName="Linnaeus. The" box="[264,635,1164,1190]" class="Insecta" family="Attelabidae" genus="Apoderus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="coryli">
<emphasis id="43F0BB02B211FF9CE259FB730FC65DFA" box="[264,454,1164,1189]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">Apoderus coryli</emphasis>
Linnaeus. The
</taxonomicName>
female briefly interrupts this rolling process to perforate the leaf roll and lay her eggs inside. In almost all the rolls that were opened there were two eggs (or two larvae, or two pupae); only one dissected roll contained a pupa and two mature larvae. Since a large basal portion of the leaf is left intact, the roll remains firmly attached to the leaf at all times and does not fall to the ground. The larva feeds and develops on the leaf tissues inside the roll, as in the rule in Apoderinae. The whole developmental cycle is quite rapid, lasting about twenty days of which the last two or three are spent as a pupa. Each adult emerges from its own round hole (
<figureCitation id="E9BF7B95B211FF9CE745FA5B0A6D5CE1" box="[1044,1133,1444,1470]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 12" captionStartId="6.[264,370,1505,1526]" captionTargetBox="[264,1322,283,1460]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[689,1325,282,893]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 12. Madapoderus pacificus n. sp.: 10 a leaf roll with two emergence holes; 11 foliage of" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/170529/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number id="C74C7537B211FF9CE71DFA5B0A6D5CE1" box="[1100,1133,1444,1470]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
). On emergence the integument of the adults is translucent pale yellow, and they remain on the leaves until it hardens and takes on its proper coloration, before commencing to feed and start a new generation. Field observations in this locality were carried out only during a few days, so I can affirm that the weevil complete at least two cycles in a year; however the speed of the life cycle indicates that the number could be higher.
</paragraph>
